{"clauses":[{"item_alias":"K1","response":"The standard requires forbidden cases to be concrete observations that could realistically have obtained, not merely logical contraries. Paleoclimatic data from Eastern Mediterranean sediment cores showing stable precipitation between 1200–1150 BC is precisely the kind of empirical finding that could realistically have been obtained—sediment cores are routinely extracted and analyzed for precipitation proxies, and a stable precipitation pattern is a physically possible outcome that would be recorded in such data. The fact that the 3.2ka event is well-supported by current evidence does not make a contrary finding unrealistic; it makes it disconfirmed, which is exactly what makes the forbidden case a meaningful test of the mechanism."}]}